{"id":14880785,"mediaExerciseId":"8b6da642-f59e-4a65-bb1e-0cf53f425a4d","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"3","chapterTitle":"Working with Financial Statements","groupId":612274,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":84,"solutions":[{"id":5908172,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we are required to determine what causes the current ratio to greatly increased and the quick ratio to fall.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":66,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/2af742213c014c7b1b6f108d4239025b/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/2af742213c014c7b1b6f108d4239025b/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"Before we begin, let us first define current ratio.\n\n**Current ratio** is a financial ratio which shows if a company can pay its current liabilities by maximizing its current assets.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Current ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Current Assets}} {\\text{Current Liabilities}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":231,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/d7a58461f818041ef75b6ac7239cc494/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":118,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/d7a58461f818041ef75b6ac7239cc494/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"Let us also define quick ratio.\n\n**Quick ratio** is a financial ratio which shows if a company can meet its short-term obligations with its most liquid assets.\n\nThe formula is denoted as follows:\n$$\\begin{aligned}\n\\textbf{Quick ratio}& =\n \\dfrac{\\text{Current Assets - Inventory}} {\\text{Current Liabilities}}\\\\ \\\\\n\\end{aligned}$$\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":231,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/6ae8ed3e02c312203fcf7c022b9e14cb/lateximg_large.png","width":995},"regular":{"height":118,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/6ae8ed3e02c312203fcf7c022b9e14cb/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"If the current ratio has greatly increased and at the same time the quick ratio has fallen, this could mean that Dixie Co. has increased their inventory. The quick ratio ignores inventory in the calculation of current assets. \n\nAssuming current liability levels has not change, liquidity will decrease will be more likely to struggle with paying short-term obligations. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":179,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/c63a296a8a0dce01868f5d9844136ca6/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/19/17e6cdd537e6ca6c8571276fd1fe450a/c63a296a8a0dce01868f5d9844136ca6/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"6b73fbd5-7c4f-4b2e-ba40-10f11df379ba","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"978125